**Example Anti-Pattern: Redundant ById Type Aliases**

**❌ DON'T: Create redundant ById type aliases**

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG: Redundant alias - no additional fields
export type Color = {
  id: number
  code: string
  translations: ColorTranslation[]
}

export type ColorById = Color // ❌ Redundant - just an alias
```

**✅ DO: Only create ById types when they extend the base type with additional fields**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: ById extends base type with additional fields
export type Role = {
  id: number
  name: string
  permission_type: 'all' | 'custom'
}

export type RoleById = Role & {
  translations?: {
    id: number
    locale: 'ar' | 'en'
    name: string
    role_id: number
  }[]
}
```

**✅ DO: Use the base type directly when ById would be redundant**

```typescript
// ✅ CORRECT: Use base type directly in queries
export const getColorByIdQuery = (colorId?: number | string) =>
  queryOptions<API<Color>, AxiosError<API>, Color | undefined>({
    // ...
  })
```

**Why:**

- Redundant type aliases add no value and create unnecessary indirection
- They increase maintenance burden (need to update both types)
- They can cause confusion about when to use which type
- Only create `{Resource}ById` when the detail endpoint returns additional fields not present in the list response
